Now I understand the issue. Looking at the `testToMapWithShortRecord` test, it creates a CSV parser with headers "A", "B", "C" but only has values "a","b" (so the third column "C" will have no value). When `toMap()` is called on this short record, it should handle the case where there are more headers than values.

Looking at the `putIn` method in CSVRecord, it iterates through all mappings regardless of whether values exist for those positions. If there are more headers than values (a "short record"), this method will throw an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` when trying to access `values[col]` for columns that don't have corresponding values.

Let me look more closely at the `putIn` method and the `toMap` method:

```java
<M extends Map<String, String>> M putIn(final M map) {
    for (final Entry<String, Integer> entry : mapping.entrySet()) {
        final int col = entry.getValue().intValue();
            map.put(entry.getKey(), values[col]);  // This line will cause ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
    }
    return map;
}
```

The issue is that the `putIn` method doesn't check if the index is within bounds before accessing `values[col]`. It should check if the column index is less than the length of values, and if not, it should put null or an empty string.

Let me implement the fix:

